data.content:
## What breaks in .NET 11

In .NET 10, the EF Core Cosmos DB provider already **blocked synchronous LINQ** by default but offered a `SyncOverAsync` opt-in (via `CosmosOptionsExtension` / `EnableSyncOverAsync()`). In .NET 11, **that opt-in is removed entirely**. All four of your methods will throw `InvalidOperationException` at runtime.

## What to fix

Convert every synchronous call to its `async` counterpart:

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key changes:**
- `ToList()` → `await ToListAsync()`
- `First()` → `await FirstAsync()`
- `Count()` → `await CountAsync()`
- `SaveChanges()` → `await SaveChangesAsync()`
- Methods return `Task<T>` and follow the `Async` naming convention

You'll also need to propagate `async/await` up through every caller in your call chain (controllers, services, etc.). The sync-over-async bridge is gone — there's no workaround in .NET 11's Cosmos provider.
